<span id="v.iv.iv.iv-p7"></span> He twits Marcion with introducing his
Christ on the scene *too soon*. He ought to have waited until the
*Creator’s* Christ (prophesied of through the Old Testament) had come.
Why allow him to be predicted, and then forbid His actual coming, by his
own arrival on the scene first? Of course, M. must be understood to deny
that the Christ of the New Testament is the subject of the Old Testament
prophecies at all.  Hence T.’s anxiety to adduce *prophecy* as the main
evidence of our Lord as being really the Creator’s Christ.

